Batchsize

The batch size defines the number of samples that will be propagated through the network.

For a batchsize of 64, the model akes the first 64 samples from the training dataset and trains the network. It then takes the next 64 samples and trains the network again. This procedure repeats until all the samples have been used.

Typically, large batch sizes tend to lead to faster training times but may result in lower accuracy and overfitting while smaller batchs sizes can provide better accuracy but can be computationally expensive and time-consuming

In [ ]:
batch_size = 64

Let's start off with writing some utilities functions which we will use later on

Utility Functions

In [ ]:
def load_images(dir, img_height, img_width, colormode, batch_size=None, seed=seed):
    """
        This function loads images from directory

        Parameters:
            dir (str): Directory path
            img_height (int): Image height
            img_width (int): Image width
            colormode (str): Color mode
            batch_size (int): Batch size
            seed (int): Seed value
    """
    data = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
        dir,
        seed=seed,
        image_size=(img_height, img_width),
        batch_size=batch_size,
        color_mode=colormode
    )

    return data
In [ ]:
def try_unbatch(data):
    """
        This function tries to unbatch the data.
        If the data is already unbatched, it returns the data as it is.
        If the data is batched, it unbatch the data and returns it.
    """
    try:
        data = data.unbatch()
    except:
        data = data

    return data
In [ ]:
# Plot the training and validation accuracy and loss at each epoch
def plot_history(model, history, epochs):
    """
        This function plots the training and validation accuracy and loss at each epoch

        Parameters:
            model (keras.models): Keras model
            history (keras.callbacks.History): History object
            epochs (int): Number of epochs
            test_data (tf.data.Dataset): Test data
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 8))

    ax = ax.ravel()

    for i, metric in enumerate(['accuracy', 'loss']):
        ax[i].plot(range(epochs), history.history[metric])
        ax[i].plot(range(epochs), history.history['val_' + metric])
        ax[i].set_title(f"Model {metric}")
        ax[i].set_xlabel("Epochs")
        ax[i].set_ylabel(metric)
        ax[i].legend(['train', 'val'])
    
    # Set y ticks for plot
    ax[0].set_yticks(list(map(lambda x: round(x, ndigits=2), np.linspace(0, 1, 11).tolist())))
    ax[1].set_yticks(list(map(lambda x: round(x, ndigits=2), np.linspace(0, 3, 13).tolist())))
In [ ]:
def save_model_performance(df, model, hist, dataName):
    """
        This function saves the model performance in a dataframe

        Parameters:
            df (pandas.core.frame.DataFrame): Pandas dataframe
            model (keras.models): Keras model
            hist (keras.callbacks.History): History object
            dataName (str): Data name
    """
    model_hist = {}
    model_hist["Data"] = dataName

    for keys in ['loss', 'accuracy', 'val_loss', 'val_accuracy']:
        model_hist[f"Mean {keys}"] = np.array(hist.history[keys]).mean()
        
    # Convert to pandas dataframe with index as model name
    return pd.concat([df, pd.DataFrame(model_hist, index=[model.name])])

In [ ]:
def plot_images(data, n_rows=3,n_cols=5, cmap=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=(n_cols*2, n_rows*1.8))

    seen_labels = set()
    num_plots = 0

    try_unbatch(data)

    # data.take takes a random batch of images with size specified
    for images, labels in data:
        if classes[labels] not in seen_labels:
            plt.subplot(n_rows, n_cols, num_plots+1)
            # By default, imshow() uses a cmap of viridis
            plt.imshow(images.numpy().astype('uint16'), cmap=cmap)
            plt.title(classes[labels])
            plt.axis('off')

            seen_labels.add(classes[labels])
            num_plots+=1

        counter[classes[label]] = 1
    else:
        counter[classes[label]] += 1

Image Averaging¶

Image Averaging is the process of stacking multiple photos on top of each other and averaging them together. The main purpose is to see the noise of the image as well as observe all images in the dataset

Now let us see what is the average image for each class label to see how similar each image is

In [ ]:
def plot_avg_images(data, n_rows=3, n_cols=5, cmap=None, title=""):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=(24, 10))

    X_train = np.array([img[0].numpy() for img in data])
    y_train = np.array([label[1].numpy() for label in data])

    plt.suptitle(title, fontfamily='serif', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')

    seen_labels = set()
    num_plots = 0

    try_unbatch(data)

    # data.take takes a random batch of images with size specified
    for idx, subplot in enumerate(ax.ravel()):
            avg_image = np.mean(X_train[np.squeeze(y_train == idx)], axis=0) / 255
            subplot.imshow(avg_image, cmap='gray')
            subplot.set_title(classes[idx], fontfamily='serif', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
            subplot.axis('off')

  • To reduce the impact of variations and emphasize on the more imporatant features, we can try and apply techniques such as histogram equalization or contrast stretching

Model Training¶

Part 1: Training the model for 128x128 images¶

Baseline Model (CNN)¶

CNN Layers Explained

Convolutional Layer

A convolutional layer is the core building block of the CNN. This layer performs a dot product between two matrices where one matrix is the set of learnable parameters known as a kernel/filters. The kernel is spatially smaller than an image but is more in depth. During the forward pass, the kernel slides across the height and width of the image-producing the image representation of that region.

In keras, the kernel_size parameter referes to the size of these convolution kernels. It is usually specified as a tuple where (3,3) would mean that the kernel is a 3x3 matrix. The filter parameter refers to the number of different kernels that are used in the convolution operation so filters=100 means that 100 different 3x3 kernels are used to conlve with the input data.

The sliding size of the kernel is called a stride. In keras, the stride of a kernel can be specified using strides.

Everytime we apply a convolution operator, our image shrinks which can cause us to lose a lot of information because of image shrinking. To fix this issue, we can use padding where we add layers of zeros or other value outside the actual data of our image. In keras, we can specify to use padding using the parameter padding and a value of 'same'.

Finally, we would have to specify an activation function for each convolution layer

For a convolutional layer, the output activation map will have the following dimensions $$W_{out} = \frac{W_{in} - K + 2P}{S} + 1$$ $$H_{out} = \frac{H_{in} - K + 2P}{S} + 1$$

Given

  • an image of dimensions $W_{in} X H_{in}$
  • a filter of dimension $F$ x $F$
  • Stride $S$ and padding $P$

Pooling Layer

A pooling layer is another essential component of a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN). It plays a critical role in reducing the spatial dimensions of the input data, which helps to decrease the computational complexity of the model.

The pooling operation involves sliding a two-dimensional filter over each channel of the feature map and summarizing the features lying within the region covered by the filter. This operation helps to retain the most important information while reducing the dimensionality of the data

In Keras, the pooling operation is typically performed using a MaxPooling2D or AveragePooling2D layer. The size of the pooling window and the stride can be specified using the pool_size and strides parameters respectively

Fully Connected Layer

The Fully Connected (FC) layer is used to connect the neurons between two different layers. These layers are usually placed before the output layer and form the last few layers of a CNN Architecture

The input image from the previous layers are flattened and fed to the FC layer where the classification process begins to take place. In keras, a fully connected layer can be used using Dense with the number of neurons in the fully connected layer and the activation function

Dropout

Overfitting occurs when a particular model learns to train on the noise from the training set of the data and does not generalise well to new data. To overcome this problem, a dropout layer is utilised where a few neurons are dropped from the neural network during the training process so that the model learns not to overely on just a few neurons. In keras, this can be specified with the Dropout layer and the percentage of neurons to drop

CNN Baseline Model Architecture

  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 64
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (2, 2)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 128
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 256
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Fully Connected Layer
  • Neurons: 128
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. Output Layer
  • Neurons: 15 (number of classes)
  • Activation Function: 'softmax'

Optimizer: Adam Epochs: 100

In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
BaselineModel = Sequential(
    name="BaselineModel",
    layers=[
    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

BaselineModel.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

BaselineModel.build(input_shape=(None, 128, 128, 1))

BaselineModel.summary()

epochs = 100
BaselineModel_history = BaselineModel.fit(
    train_128.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_128.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs
)

Adding Additional Data using Data Augmentation¶

In order to try and further improve the performance of our baseline model, we can try to add in additional data into our dataset by using data augmentation. Data Augmentation is a method to reduce the variance of a model by imposing random transformations on the data for training

The first augmentation that will be done will be rescaling the pixels in the images from a range of [0, 255] to a range of [0, 1]

In [ ]:
rescale = keras.Sequential(
    name="data_rescaling",
    layers=[
        Rescaling(1.0/255), # Value Preprocessing
    ]
)

Instead of directly applying the rescale model to our training dataset, we will be using it as the first layer in our later model so that the rescaling is applied in the model before the input is fed in

In [ ]:
# Split the dataset into X_train and y_train
data = [(img.numpy(), classes[labels]) for img, labels in train_128]

# Convert the list to numpy arrays
X_train = np.array([img for img, label in data])
y_train = np.array([label for img, label in data])

There are many different types of Image Data Augmentations but in this case, we will be using:

  • Rescaling (refer to above)
  • Rotation
  • Zooming
  • Shifting
  • Shearing
  • Flipping

Reasons for using each Data Augmentation

Rotation

Rotation is applied to train a model to avoid overfitting by introducing diversity in the data. The main advantage of rotation is that it doesn't change the meaning of the data entirely if applied to a certain extent.

Zooming

Image zooming randomly zooms the image in and adds new pixel values around the image or interpolates pixel values respectively. Image zooming is used to make the model more robust to changes in scale and perspective and better equipped to handle variations in objects sizes.

Shifting

Shifting or translation is used to make the object off-center from the image which ensures that the model learns to recognize patterns regardless of the object's exact location.

Shearing

Shearing involves changing the shape of an object by shifting each point within the object by a certain amount in a specified direction. Shearing helps the model generalize better to objects that may be viewed from different angles or perspectives

Flipping

Flipping is used to increase the dataset's size during training and is often applied randomly on images to reduce overfitting and introduce diversity in the data

Custom Data Augmentation

Center Crop

Implementation

Other than the data augmentation methods from keras, we can use custom data augmentation methods. In this case, we will be building a custom function to crop the image and get the center based on the specified crop_scale. The function will not be called all of the time but only p% of the time.


Technique Explanation

Center cropping is quite similar to random cropping. However, the main difference between center cropping and random cropping is that the cropping only results in the center of the image for center cropping. The main reason for using this technique is when the center portion of the image contains more information than the center which forces the model to learn from the center portion of the image rather than the corners

In [ ]:
# Custom Data Augmentation function
def center_crop_img(img, crop_scale=0.95, p=0.8):
    """
    Center crop an image

    Parameters
    ----------
    img : ndarray
        Image to be center cropped
    crop_scale : float (from 0 to 1)
        Scale of the crop
    p : float (from 0 to 1)
        Probability of applying the augmentation
    """

    # Check crop_scale and p are between 0 and 1
    assert 0 < crop_scale <= 1, "crop_scale must be in the range (0, 1]"
    assert 0 <= p <= 1, "p must be in the range [0, 1]" 

    # Use random choice to decide whether to apply the augmentation
    if random.random() > p:
        return img

    # Get crop size from crop_scale
    height, width = img.shape[0], img.shape[1]
    crop_size = (int(height*crop_scale), int(width*crop_scale))

    dy, dx = crop_size
    x = (width - dx) // 2
    y = (height - dy) // 2

    img = img[y:(y+dy), x:(x+dx)]

    # Resize back to original size
    img = tf.image.resize(img, (height, width), method='nearest')


    return img
In [ ]:
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
        rotation_range=40, # rotation
        zoom_range=0.2, # zoom
        width_shift_range=0.2, # horizontal shift
        height_shift_range=0.2, # vertical shift
        shear_range=0.2, # shear
        horizontal_flip=True, # horizontal flip
        fill_mode = 'reflect', # fill mode
        preprocessing_function=center_crop_img # center crop
)

# Generate images in batches of 256
aug_iter = datagen.flow(x=X_train, y=y_train, batch_size=256)
print("Previous shape: ", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)

# Generate batch of images 
for i in range(60):
        image, label=next(aug_iter)

        X_train = np.append(X_train, image, axis=0)
        y_train = np.append(y_train, label)

print("New shape: ", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)

Previous shape:  (9028, 128, 128, 1) (9028,)
New shape:  (24200, 128, 128, 1) (24200,)
In [ ]:
class_to_index = {class_name: index for index, class_name in enumerate(classes)}
y_train_int = np.array([class_to_index[label] for label in y_train])
In [ ]:
# Join x_train and y_train together and add it back to the train_128 dataset
aug_train_128 = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, y_train_int))
In [ ]:
aug_counter = {}
for img, label in aug_train_128:
    if classes[label] not in aug_counter:
        aug_counter[classes[label]] = 1
    else:
        aug_counter[classes[label]] += 1

labels, counts = np.array(list(aug_counter.keys())), np.array(list(aug_counter.values()))

labels = labels[counts.argsort()[::-1]]
counts = counts[counts.argsort()[::-1]]

counts_df = pd.DataFrame(counts, columns=['counts'], index=labels)

display(counts_df)

Improvements Made for DataAugModel:¶

  • An additional rescale model at the front which rescales the input images from a range of [0, 255] to a range of [0, 1] before feeding the rescaled data into the model
  • Instead of feeding in the original data (train_128), the dataset with augmentation is fed into the model (aug_train_128). This increases our training data from 9,000 to around 24,000
  • Decrease the learning rate by 25% from the default of 0.001 to a slightly smaller learning rate of 0.00025 to try and reduce the flucutations seen in the learning curve of the baseline model
In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
DataAugModel = Sequential(
    name="DataAugModel",
    layers=[

    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

DataAugModel.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_25),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

DataAugModel.build(input_shape=(None, 128, 128, 1))

DataAugModel.summary()

epochs = 100
DataAugModel_history = DataAugModel.fit(
    aug_train_128.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_128.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs
)

Observations:

  • Although there is still a bit of fluctuation at the start at around 20 epochs, in general, the fluctuation of the model has seemed to decrease for the validation set
  • The validation accuracy has also seemed to increase to around 90% and the loss has decreased to the range of around 0.25 to 0.5
  • With the addition of data augmentation and by slightly reudcing the learning rate, the performance of the model seems to have improved quite a bit

Improving Architecture of CNN Model¶

In order to try and improve our models, here are some things we can change in our model's architecture:

  • Increase number of convolutional layers: In order to try and capture more complex features, we can try to increase the number of convolutional layers being used in the model from 3 to 5 with the two additional layers sharing a max pooling layer
  • Increase kernel size: In order to try and detect larger features, we can try and increase the kernel size of our model for the first few layers instead of just using a consistent kernel size of (3, 3)
  • Increase number of FC layers: Instead of just using one FC layer, we can use two FC layers
  • Add BatchNormalization: In order to try and reduce overfitting, we can use batch normalization to make the model more stable by normalizing the inputs through re-centering and re-scaling

With these new chages, here is the new architecture of the model

CNN Improved Model Architecture

  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 32
  • Kernel Size: (7, 7)
  • Strides: (2, 2)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 64
  • Kernel Size: (5, 5)
  • Strides: (2, 2)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 128
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 256
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 512
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Fully Connected Layer
  • Neurons: 256
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. Fully Connected Layer
  • Neurons: 128
  • Activation Function: 'relu'

  1. Batch Normalization

  2. Output Layer

  • Neurons: 15 (number of classes)
  • Activation Function: 'softmax'

Optimizer: Adam (learning rate = 0.000,25) Epochs: 100

Improvements made for ImprovedArchModel:¶

  • An additional two layers with filter sizes of 256 and 512 have been added with a shared max pooling layer
  • The first layer starts of with an even smaller filter size of 32
  • The kernel size for the first two layers have been increased ot (7, 7) and (5, 5) respectively to detect larger features
  • The stride for second layer is increased from (1, 1) to (2, 2)
  • An additional fully connected layer with 256 neurons is added after the first fully connected layer
  • Added BatchNormalization to make the model more stable and reduce any possible overfitting
In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
ImprovedArchModel = Sequential(
    name="ImprovedArchitectureModel",
    layers=[
    # Preprocessing Layer
    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=7, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=5, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),
    
    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

ImprovedArchModel.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_25),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

ImprovedArchModel.build(input_shape=(None, 128, 128, 1))

ImprovedArchModel.summary()

epochs = 100
ImprovedArchModel_history = ImprovedArchModel.fit(
    aug_train_128.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_128.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs
)

Balancing Classes using Data Augmentation¶

As seen previously during the EDA, the number of images for each vegetable is not balanced with vegetables like tomato having as many as 900 images and other vegetables as radish only having 200 images

Instead of just adding data randomly using data augmentation to reduce the variance of our model, we can also use data augmentation to strategically add the number of images for each class such that it becomes more balanced. By doing so, our model will have enough training data for each class

In [ ]:
# Clear memory in space
# IMPORTANT STEP OTHERWISE DATASET CANNOT BE CREATED
del aug_train_128
In [ ]:
display(counter)

In [ ]:
# Split the dataset into X_train and y_train
data = [(img.numpy(), classes[labels]) for img, labels in train_128]

# Convert the list to numpy arrays
X_train = np.array([img for img, label in data])
y_train = np.array([label for img, label in data])

In order to balance the classes, we will try to use increase the number of images for each class to a value of $N$ (where in this case, $N$ = 1750).

The eventual number of images generated however, will not be exactly the value $N$ but will be $$ImagesGenerated = {\lfloor \frac{N - CurrentNumberOfImages}{BatchSize} \rfloor} $$

When using ImageDataGenerator, generating the images one by one will be too slow so the images are usually generated in batches where a larger batch size will generate images quicker.

However, using a larger batch size means that we have less control over how many images get generated so the number of classes of each vegetable might be quite far from $N$.

As such, we will try to use a batch size of 32 so that we have some control over how many images get generated but the generation proces won't take too long

In [ ]:
# Split the training data into different classes
train_128_ds = {}

for vegetable in classes:
    mask = y_train == vegetable
    train_128_ds[vegetable] = X_train[mask]

aug_batch_size = 32

N = 1750

# Get the number of images to generate for each class and convert it to the nearest
num_batches = {vegetable: (N - counter[vegetable]) // aug_batch_size for vegetable in classes}

# Generate images for each class
for vegetable in classes:
    print(f"[{classes.index(vegetable)+1}/15] Generating Images for: {vegetable}")
    aug_iter = datagen.flow(x=train_128_ds[vegetable], y=[vegetable]*len(train_128_ds[vegetable]), batch_size=aug_batch_size)
    print("Initial Length: ", len(train_128_ds[vegetable]))
    print("Adding", num_batches[vegetable]*aug_batch_size, "Images")
    for i in range(num_batches[vegetable]):
        image, label=next(aug_iter)
        train_128_ds[vegetable] = np.append(train_128_ds[vegetable], image, axis=0)

    print("Current Length: ", len(train_128_ds[vegetable]))
    print('\n')

# Concatenate all the images together
X_train_bal = np.concatenate([train_128_ds[vegetable] for vegetable in classes], axis=0)
y_train_bal = np.concatenate([[vegetable]*len(train_128_ds[vegetable]) for vegetable in classes], axis=0)

print("New Shape: ", X_train_bal.shape, y_train_bal.shape)

# Convert the labels to integers
y_train_bal_int = np.array([class_to_index[label] for label in y_train_bal])

# This won't run if the previous dataset is not deleted or if there is not enough memory

In [ ]:
counter = {}
for img, label in bal_train_128:
    if classes[label] not in counter:
        counter[classes[label]] = 1
    else:
        counter[classes[label]] += 1

labels, counts = np.array(list(counter.keys())), np.array(list(counter.values()))

Observations:

  • Although the number of images are not exactly the same, they are close enough such that they all make up 6% of the data
  • From the graph, we can now see that our training set is balanced

Improvements Made for DataAugModel:¶

  • Instead of feeding in the dataset with augmentation (aug_train_128), the balanced dataset with augmentation is fed into the model (bal_train_128). This increases our training slightly data from 24,200 to around 25,700 but more importantly, it balances the number of images to around 1750 for each class
In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation and balancing
BalModel = Sequential(
    name="BalancedModel",
    layers=[
    # Preprocessing Layer
    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=7, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=5, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),
    
    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),

    Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

BalModel.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_25),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

BalModel.build(input_shape=(None, 128, 128, 1))

BalModel.summary()

epochs = 100
BalModel_history = BalModel.fit(
    bal_train_128.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_128.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs,
)

Using a Learning Rate Scheduler¶

Instead of using a constant learning rate throughout when training the model, we can use an adaptive learning rate that is being adjusted between epochs. In keras, this can be implemented with the LearningRateScheduler callback.

Common learning rate schedules include:

  • Time-Based Decay
  • Step-Based Decay
  • Exponential Decay

Time-Based Decay

$$ \begin{equation} Rate\_{n} := Rate\_{n-1} \cdot \frac{1}{1 + Decay \cdot Epoch} \nonumber \end{equation} $$

In the above formula, the learning rate is being update by a factor of $\frac{1}{1 + Decay * Epoch}$ which is based on the rate of Decay specified and the number of Epochs the model has been through.

A common value of used for Decay is $$Decay = \frac{Rate\_{1}}{Epoch}$$

where the initial learning rate at the first epoch is used to calculate the Decay

In keras, a time-based decay learning rate scheduler can be defined as follows:

def timeDecay(epoch, lr):
    initial_lr = 0.000_25
    # + 1 to avoid division by 0
    decay = initial_lr/(epoch+1)
    return lr * 1/ (1 + decay * epoch)

Step-Based Decay

In step-based decay, the learning rate is systematically dropped by a factor every few epochs. The formula can be described as: $$ \begin{equation} Rate\_{n} := Rate\_{n-1} \cdot DropRate^{\lfloor \frac{Epoch}{EpochDrop} \rfloor} \nonumber \end{equation} $$

In keras, a step-based decay learning rate scheduler can be defined as follows:

def stepDecay(epoch, lr):
    dropRate = 0.5
    epochsDrop = 10.0
    return lr * np.power(dropRate, np.floor((1+epoch)/epochsDrop))

In the above formula, the learning rate is being dropped by the factor $DropRate$ after every $EpochDrop$ number of Epochs


Exponential-Based Decay

In Exponential Based Decay, the decay is defined as an exponential function of the number of epochs in the following equation: $$ \begin{equation} Rate\_{n} := Rate\_{n-1} \cdot e^{k \cdot Epoch} \nonumber \end{equation} $$

Exponential Based Decay tends to decay much faster compared to time-based decay

In keras, a exponential-based decay learning rate scheduler can be defined as follows:

def expDecay(epoch, lr):
    k = 0.001
    return lr * np.exp(-k * epoch)

Comparing the Learning Rate for different schedulers:

Image from neptune.ai

From the above image, we can see that exponential based decay decays much faster compared to time based decay initially but eventually, they will both decay to a very small learning where the change in learning rate becomes very small

As for step-based decay, it decays the slowest and it also does not decay to the point close to zero like time-based decay or exponential-decay

For the training of our model, we will be using time based decay. However based on testing, the decay is not fast enough so we can speed it up by an additional factor $k$

In [ ]:
def timeDecay(epoch, lr):
    initial_lr = 0.000_25
    # Use k to speed up the decay
    k = 100
    # + 1 to avoid division by 0
    decay = initial_lr/(epoch+1)
    return lr * 1/ (1 + k * decay * epoch)

learningRateScheduler = keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(timeDecay)

# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
FinalModel = Sequential(
    name="FinalModel",
    layers=[
    # Preprocessing Layer
    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=7, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=5, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),
    
    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),

    Conv2D(filters=512, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

FinalModel.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_25),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

FinalModel.build(input_shape=(None, 128, 128, 1))

FinalModel.summary()

epochs = 100
FinalModel_history = FinalModel.fit(
    bal_train_128.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_128.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs,
    callbacks=[learningRateScheduler]
)

plot_history(FinalModel, FinalModel_history, epochs)

Observations:

  • From the learning curve, the fluctuations in the accuracy are pretty much non-existent
  • The model loss has also improved significantly with it mostly being completely below 0.25 which is quite a good improvement compared to the model loss of around 1 from the baseline CNN
  • With the learning rate scheduler, it seems that the learning rate decays to a very small value at the end as seen by how the accuracy at the end barely changes

Part 2: Training the model for 31x31 images¶

Baseline Model (CNN)¶

For our 31x31 model, we will start off with a baseline model which is slightly simpler compared to the one used to train the 128x128 images by removing the last convolutional layer

This is because for smaller images, simpler models are generally more effective

Batchsize

We would also be using a smaller batch size for the 31x31 model since its training will typically be faster compared to the 128x128 model so we can afford to reduce the batch size and increase the training time slightly more

In [ ]:
batch_size=31

CNN Baseline Model Architecture

  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 64
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (2, 2)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 128
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Fully Connected Layer
  • Neurons: 128
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. Output Layer
  • Neurons: 15 (number of classes)
  • Activation Function: 'softmax'

Optimizer: Adam Epochs: 100

In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
BaselineModel31 = Sequential(
    name="BaselineModel",
    layers=[
    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(31, 31, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

BaselineModel31.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

BaselineModel31.build(input_shape=(None, 31, 31, 1))

BaselineModel31.summary()

epochs = 100
BaselineModel31_history = BaselineModel31.fit(
    train_31.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_31.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs
)

Adding Additional Data using Data Augmentation¶

In order to try and further improve the performance of our baseline model, we can try to add in additional data into our dataset by using data augmentation. Data Augmentation is a method to reduce the variance of a model by imposing random transformations on the data for training

The first augmentation that will be done will be rescaling the pixels in the images from a range of [0, 255] to a range of [0, 1]

In [ ]:
rescale = keras.Sequential(
    name="data_rescaling",
    layers=[
        Rescaling(1.0/255), # Value Preprocessing
    ]
)
In [ ]:
# Split the dataset into X_train and y_train
data = [(img.numpy(), classes[labels]) for img, labels in train_31]

# Convert the list to numpy arrays
X_train = np.array([img for img, label in data])
y_train = np.array([label for img, label in data])

Reasons for not using Zoom and Center Crop

We will mostly be using similar data augmentation techniques used in the 128x128 model. However, we will not be using zooming and center cropping since the images are already very small

This is because techniques like zoom and center croping will choose a specific part of the image to focus on which can be useful in scenarios where the object of interest in the image varies in size.

However, for smaller images like 31x31 pixels, zooming can be problematic since we are essentially ncreasing the size of the image without adding any new information. This can lead to a loss of detail and potentially distort the image, which can negatively impact the performance of our model

On the other hand, for larger images like 128x128 pixels, zooming can be more beneficial since they typically contain more detail and can handle more distortions without losing significant information.

In [ ]:
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
        rotation_range=10, # rotation
        width_shift_range=0.1, # horizontal shift
        height_shift_range=0.1, # vertical shift
        shear_range=0.1, # shear
        horizontal_flip=True, # horizontal flip
)

# Generate images in batches of 256
aug_iter = datagen.flow(x=X_train, y=y_train, batch_size=256)
print("Previous shape: ", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)

# Generate batch of images 
for i in range(60):
        image, label=next(aug_iter)

        X_train = np.append(X_train, image, axis=0)
        y_train = np.append(y_train, label)

print("New shape: ", X_train.shape, y_train.shape)

Previous shape:  (9028, 31, 31, 1) (9028,)
New shape:  (24200, 31, 31, 1) (24200,)
In [ ]:
class_to_index = {class_name: index for index, class_name in enumerate(classes)}
y_train_int = np.array([class_to_index[label] for label in y_train])
In [ ]:
# SHuffle the data
X_train, y_train_int = shuffle(X_train, y_train_int, random_state=seed)
In [ ]:
# Join x_train and y_train together and add it back to the train_31 dataset
aug_train_31 = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, y_train_int))
In [ ]:
aug_counter = {}
for img, label in aug_train_31:
    if classes[label] not in aug_counter:
        aug_counter[classes[label]] = 1
    else:
        aug_counter[classes[label]] += 1

labels, counts = np.array(list(aug_counter.keys())), np.array(list(aug_counter.values()))

labels = labels[counts.argsort()[::-1]]
counts = counts[counts.argsort()[::-1]]

counts_df = pd.DataFrame(counts, columns=['counts'], index=labels)

display(counts_df)

Improvements Made for DataAugModel:¶

  • An additional rescale model at the front which rescales the input images from a range of [0, 255] to a range of [0, 1] before feeding the rescaled data into the model
  • Instead of feeding in the original data (train_31), the dataset with augmentation is fed into the model (aug_train_31). This increases our training data from 9,000 to around 24,000
  • Decrease the learning rate by 50% from the default of 0.001 to a slightly smaller learning rate of 0.0005 to try and help improve the models performance
In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
DataAugModel31 = Sequential(
    name="DataAugModel",
    layers=[
    rescale,
    
    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, strides=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(31, 31, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

DataAugModel31.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_5),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

DataAugModel31.build(input_shape=(None, 31, 31, 1))

DataAugModel31.summary()

epochs = 100
DataAugModel31_history = DataAugModel31.fit(
    aug_train_31.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_31.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs
)

Improving Architecture of CNN Model¶

In order to try and improve our models, here are some things we can change in our model's architecture:

  • Increase number of convolutional layers: In order to try and capture more complex features, we can try to increase the number of convolutional layers being used in the model from 2 to 3 with an additional convolutional layer of 256
  • Increase kernel size: In order to try and detect larger features, we can try and increase the kernel size of our model for the first few layer to (5, 5)
  • Add BatchNormalization: In order to try and reduce overfitting, we can use batch normalization to make the model more stable by normalizing the inputs through re-centering and re-scaling

With these new chages, here is the new architecture of the model

CNN Improved Model Architecture

  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 64
  • Kernel Size: (5, 5)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 128
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling
  • Pool Size: (2, 2)
  1. Convolutional Layer
  • Filters: 256
  • Kernel Size: (3, 3)
  • Strides: (1, 1)
  • Padding: 'same'
  • Activation Function: 'relu'
  1. MaxPooling

  • Pool Size: (2, 2)

  • Activation Function: 'relu'

  1. Fully Connected Layer
  • Neurons: 128
  • Activation Function: 'relu'

  1. Batch Normalization

  2. Output Layer

  • Neurons: 15 (number of classes)
  • Activation Function: 'softmax'

Optimizer: Adam (learning rate = 0.000,5) Epochs: 100

In [ ]:
# Model with data augmentation but no balancing
ImprovedArchModel31 = Sequential(
    name="ImprovedArchitectureModel",
    layers=[
    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=5, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(31, 31, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

ImprovedArchModel31.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_5),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

ImprovedArchModel31.build(input_shape=(None, 31, 31, 1))

ImprovedArchModel31.summary()

epochs = 100
ImprovedArchModel31_history = ImprovedArchModel31.fit(
    aug_train_31.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_31.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs
)

Balancing Classes using Data Augmentation¶

As seen previously during the EDA, the number of images for each vegetable is not balanced with vegetables like tomato having as many as 900 images and other vegetables as radish only having 200 images

Instead of just adding data randomly using data augmentation to reduce the variance of our model, we can also use data augmentation to strategically add the number of images for each class such that it becomes more balanced. By doing so, our model will have enough training data for each class

In [ ]:
# Clear memory in space
# IMPORTANT STEP OTHERWISE DATASET CANNOT BE CREATED
del aug_train_31
In [ ]:
# Split the dataset into X_train and y_train
data = [(img.numpy(), classes[labels]) for img, labels in train_31]

# Convert the list to numpy arrays
X_train = np.array([img for img, label in data])
y_train = np.array([label for img, label in data])
In [ ]:
counter = {}
for label in y_train:
    if label not in counter:
        counter[label] = 1
    else:
        counter[label] += 1

In order to balance the classes, we will try to use increase the number of images for each class to a value of $N$ (where in this case, $N$ = 1750).

The eventual number of images generated however, will not be exactly the value $N$ but will be $$ImagesGenerated = {\lfloor \frac{N - CurrentNumberOfImages}{BatchSize} \rfloor} $$

When using ImageDataGenerator, generating the images one by one will be too slow so the images are usually generated in batches where a larger batch size will generate images quicker.

However, using a larger batch size means that we have less control over how many images get generated so the number of classes of each vegetable might be quite far from $N$.

As such, we will try to use a batch size of 32 so that we have some control over how many images get generated but the generation proces won't take too long

In [ ]:
# Split the training data into different classes
train_31_ds = {}

for vegetable in classes:
    mask = y_train == vegetable
    train_31_ds[vegetable] = X_train[mask]

aug_batch_size = 32

N = 1750

# Get the number of images to generate for each class and convert it to the nearest
num_batches = {vegetable: (N - counter[vegetable]) // aug_batch_size for vegetable in classes}

# Generate images for each class
for vegetable in classes:
    print(f"[{classes.index(vegetable)+1}/15] Generating Images for: {vegetable}")
    aug_iter = datagen.flow(x=train_31_ds[vegetable], y=[vegetable]*len(train_31_ds[vegetable]), batch_size=aug_batch_size)
    print("Initial Length: ", len(train_31_ds[vegetable]))
    print("Adding", num_batches[vegetable]*aug_batch_size, "Images")
    for i in range(num_batches[vegetable]):
        image, label=next(aug_iter)
        train_31_ds[vegetable] = np.append(train_31_ds[vegetable], image, axis=0)

    print("Current Length: ", len(train_31_ds[vegetable]))
    print('\n')

# Concatenate all the images together
X_train_bal = np.concatenate([train_31_ds[vegetable] for vegetable in classes], axis=0)
y_train_bal = np.concatenate([[vegetable]*len(train_31_ds[vegetable]) for vegetable in classes], axis=0)

print("New Shape: ", X_train_bal.shape, y_train_bal.shape)

Observations:

  • Although the number of images are not exactly the same, they are close enough such that they all make up 6% of the data
  • From the graph, we can now see that our training set is balanced

Improvements Made for DataAugModel:¶

  • Instead of feeding in the dataset with augmentation (aug_train_31), the balanced dataset with augmentation is fed into the model (bal_train_31). This increases our training slightly data from 24,200 to around 25,700 but more importantly, it balances the number of images to around 1750 for each class
In [ ]:
BalModel31 = Sequential(
    name="BalancedModel",
    layers=[
    # Preprocessing Layer
    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=5, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(31, 31, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

BalModel31.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_5),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

BalModel31.build(input_shape=(None, 31, 31, 1))

BalModel31.summary()

epochs = 100
BalModel31_history = BalModel31.fit(
    bal_train_31.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_31.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs,
)

Using a Learning Rate Scheduler¶

For the training of our model, we will still be using time based decay. However we will reduce the value of $k$ to 25 instead of 100

In [ ]:
def timeDecay31(epoch, lr):
    initial_lr = 0.000_25
    # Use k to speed up the decay
    k = 25
    # + 1 to avoid division by 0
    decay = initial_lr/(epoch+1)
    return lr * 1/ (1 + k * decay * epoch)

learningRateScheduler31 = keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(timeDecay31)
In [ ]:
FinalModel31 = Sequential(
    name="FinalModel",
    layers=[
    # Preprocessing Layer
    rescale,

    Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=5, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(31, 31, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, strides=1, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),

    Flatten(),
    Dropout(0.6),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

FinalModel31.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.000_5),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

FinalModel31.build(input_shape=(None, 31, 31, 1))

FinalModel31.summary()

epochs = 100
FinalModel31_history = FinalModel31.fit(
    bal_train_31.batch(batch_size),
    validation_data=val_31.batch(batch_size),
    epochs=epochs,
    callbacks=[learningRateScheduler31]
)

Model Evaluation¶

Let us look at how both of our final model performs on the test dataset and compare their performances

In [ ]:
print("EVALUATION FOR 31x31 MODEL")
test_loss, test_acc = FinalModel31.evaluate(test_31.batch(32))
print("Test Loss: ", test_loss)
print("Test Accuracy: ", test_acc)

print(f"\n{'-'*100}")

print("EVALUATION FOR 128x128 MODEL")
test_loss, test_acc = FinalModel.evaluate(test_128.batch(64))
print("Test Loss: ", test_loss)
print("Test Accuracy: ", test_acc)

Let us also evaluate both models using scikit learn's classification report which will produce a report with the precision, recall and F1-score for each class

In [ ]:
# Get X_test and y_test
data = [(img.numpy(), classes[labels]) for img, labels in test_31]

# Convert the list to numpy arrays
X_test = np.array([img for img, label in data])
y_test = np.array([label for img, label in data])

# Convert y_test to integer labels
y_test_int = np.array([class_to_index[label] for label in y_test])

y_pred = BalModel31.predict(X_test)

report31 = classification_report(
    y_test_int,
    np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1),
    target_names=classes
)

Observations:

  • From the classification report, we can see that our 128x128 model has performed very well with a precision, recall and f1-score of all around 0.97
  • The scores for each vegetable is also not very far off from one another which shows that our model has learned to generalise well for all the different vegetables
  • Our 31x31 model has also performed quite well but there is slightly more variation like how Radish has a 100% precision while Cabbage only has 85%
  • Overall both models have performed quite well with the 31x31 model having a weighted average of 94% and the 128x128 model having a weighted average of 97%

Since we used about the similar improvement steps to derive our final model, let us take a look at how much each step has improved the overall performance of the model

In [ ]:
print("31X31 Models")
display(perf_31_models)
print("128X128 Models")
display(perf_128_models)

31X31 Models
Data Mean loss Mean accuracy Mean val_loss Mean val_accuracy
BaselineModel Original 0.539683 0.832223 0.960666 0.758427
DataAugModel Augmented 0.335942 0.888484 0.414776 0.884810
ImprovedArchitectureModel Augmented 0.155620 0.948706 0.273531 0.928207
BalancedModel Balanced Augmented 0.148900 0.950973 0.283400 0.927940
FinalModel Balanced Augmented 0.136447 0.955361 0.281167 0.927093 
128X128 Models
Data Mean loss Mean accuracy Mean val_loss Mean val_accuracy
BaselineModel Original 0.177107 0.948607 0.749330 0.865227
DataAugModel Augmented 0.164322 0.946507 0.509775 0.877827
ImprovedArchitectureModel Augmented 0.142283 0.954847 0.348815 0.916610
BalancedModel Balanced Augmented 0.134344 0.956594 0.245093 0.940640
FinalModel Balanced Augmented 0.140035 0.955882 0.242838 0.942030

Observations:

  • Comparing the baseline models, the 128x182 model has a much better performance but eventually, both were able to improve to a mean validation accuracy of above 90 percent
  • For the 31x31 model, data augmentation managed to help improve the performance a lot dropping the mean validation loss from 0.96 to 0.41 and improving the model architecture helped improve it even further by reducing the validation loss to around 0.27. Howver after that, Balancing the Data and adding a learning rate scheduler did not help much in terms of the model's overall performance even though they did help slightly with the final validation accuracy
  • This is also quite similar in the 128x128 model where data augmentation helped to significantly reduce the loss and improving the model architecture help further reduce it. However, in the 128x128 model, balancing the dataset alo seemed to have help improve the model which was not the case for the 31x31 model

Final Thoughts on both models:

  • Overall, its seems that the 128x128 model has a better performance compared to the 31x31 model in terms of both accuracy and loss. However, the improvement in the performance is not a lot and the 31x31 model already has a very good performance on its on
  • Another thing to note is that the 128x128 model took significantly longer to train compared to the 31x31 model in terms of both running the model and for the data augmentation where augmenting the 128x128 model took as long as one minute while augmenting te 31x31 model was much shorter at only a few seconds
  • This means that if the perfect model is not needed and time is a huge concern, it would be better to go with a smaller image size like the 31x31 model since training it would be much shorter. However, if the goal is to have the best model possible, it would make more sense to use an even larger image size like the 128x128 model though in some cases like this one, the improvement won't be very drastic

Save Models¶

Save all the models as a h5 file

In [ ]:
dir = os.path.join(os.getcwd(), "CNN_Models")

if not os.path.exists(dir):
    os.mkdir(dir)
else:
    for file in os.listdir(dir):
        os.remove(os.path.join(dir, file))

dir_31 = os.path.join(dir, "31")
dir_128 = os.path.join(dir, "128")

if not os.path.exists(dir_31):
    os.mkdir(dir_31)
else:
    for file in os.listdir(dir_31):
        os.remove(os.path.join(dir_31, file))

BaselineModel31.save(os.path.join(dir_31, "BaselineModel_31.h5"))
DataAugModel31.save(os.path.join(dir_31, "DataAugModel_31.h5"))
ImprovedArchModel31.save(os.path.join(dir_31, "ImprovedArchModel_31.h5"))
BalModel31.save(os.path.join(dir_31, "BalModel_31.h5"))
FinalModel31.save(os.path.join(dir_31, "FinalModel_31.h5"))

if not os.path.exists(dir_128):
    os.mkdir(dir_128)
else:
    for file in os.listdir(dir_128):
        os.remove(os.path.join(dir_128, file))

BaselineModel.save(os.path.join(dir_128, "BaselineModel_128.h5"))
DataAugModel.save(os.path.join(dir_128, "DataAugModel_128.h5"))
ImprovedArchModel.save(os.path.join(dir_128, "ImprovedArchModel_128.h5"))
BalModel.save(os.path.join(dir_128, "BalModel_128.h5"))
FinalModel.save(os.path.join(dir_128, "FinalModel_128.h5"))
